  <h1>Common Late-Pay Misconceptions</h1>
  <p>Both vendors and customers — and employees and employers — commonly misunderstand late-payment rules. The most frequent mistaken beliefs:</p>

  <h2>"I can charge any late fee I want"</h2>
  <p><strong>Wrong.</strong> State usury laws cap interest rates. Late fees considered "penalties" (unreasonably large compared to actual damages) may be unenforceable. Late fees not disclosed in advance are typically unenforceable.</p>

  <h2>"If my contract doesn't mention late fees, I can't charge any"</h2>
  <p><strong>Mostly wrong.</strong> Even without a contractual rate, you can usually claim statutory interest at the state's commercial rate when you sue. Not as good as having it in writing, but you're not entirely without recourse.</p>

  <h2>"Late fees become part of the invoice automatically"</h2>
  <p><strong>Wrong.</strong> Late fees must be properly invoiced and supported by contractual or statutory authority. Surprise additions don't legally bind the customer.</p>

  <h2>"If my employer is one day late, I get the waiting time penalty"</h2>
  <p><strong>Depends heavily on state.</strong> California's waiting time penalty triggers immediately for involuntary terminations. Other states have grace periods or different penalty structures. Check your specific state.</p>

  <h2>"My employer can pay me with anything as long as it's something"</h2>
  <p><strong>Generally wrong.</strong> Most states require wages in cash, check, or electronic transfer. Goods, scrip, or company stock typically don't satisfy wage payment laws.</p>

  <h2>"I'm a contractor, so wage payment rules don't apply"</h2>
  <p><strong>Right but with caveat.</strong> Contractors aren't covered by wage payment laws, but contract law still gives you recourse for non-payment (with breach-of-contract and unjust-enrichment claims). The remedies differ but you're not without options.</p>

  <h2>"Compound interest is standard for late fees"</h2>
  <p><strong>Wrong.</strong> Simple interest is the default. Compound interest needs explicit contractual provision and may face stricter scrutiny.</p>

  <h2>"I can demand the entire late fee in one shot"</h2>
  <p><strong>Depends on the language.</strong> Some contracts impose late fees only when payment is more than X days late, with no accrual after that point. Others accrue daily indefinitely. Read your contract.</p>

  <h2>"State usury laws cap all late fees"</h2>
  <p><strong>Mostly wrong.</strong> Many states exempt commercial transactions from usury limits or set much higher caps. Consumer transactions are more protected. The applicable cap depends on the parties and transaction type.</p>

  <h2>"If the customer disputes the invoice, I can't charge late fees"</h2>
  <p><strong>Depends on context.</strong> If the dispute is in good faith and timely raised, late fees may not apply. If the customer is just stalling without a legitimate dispute, late fees typically continue to accrue.</p>
</BaseLayout>
